<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-231-556  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 231 556.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  March 12 1990 v7 n11 p4(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Texas hospital tests HDTV net for remote diagnosis.andO;(high-definition television)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Eckerson, Wayne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Texas Children's Hospital has demonstrated a high-definitiontelevision (HDTV) network that enables medical personnel todiagnose patients from a remote clinic.andP;  The demonstrationestablished the hospital's Center for Remote Medical Consultation,and revealed the potential for such a system to improvecommunications between specialists at city hospitals andphysicians who work in the outlying communities.andP;  HDTV offers amore color-true and detailed picture than standard television,enabling a physician to evaluate symptoms such as pupil dilation,skin color and texture.andP;  Although the demonstration was animportant one for medical technology, there are obstacles toovercome, such as developing low-cost codecs capable ofcompressing HDTV signals onto a single fiber.andP;  Small andeconomical broadband optical cross-connect switches that cansupport up to ports are also needed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Texas Children's HospitalHigh-Definition TelevisionNetworksMedical DiagnosisRemote Access.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>